ance, and the [[University of Dubuque]], where he earned a master's degree in business administration.\n\nBlum is the former CEO of Eagle Point Software (1990\u20132000). He has owned Digital Canal, a software company, since 2000.<ref>DES (May 9, 2014). [http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/politics/2014/05/09/iowa-election-rod-blum-bio-issues/8924985/ \"Iowa Election 2014\"]. ''Des Moines Register''.</ref><ref name=\"iowarepub\">[http://theiowarepublican.com/2011/rod-blum-announces-campaign-for-congress-in-1st-cd/ \"Rod Blum Announces Campaign for Congress in 1st CD | The Iowa Republican\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105063915/http://theiowarepublican.com/2011/rod-blum-announces-campaign-for-congress-in-1st-cd/ |date=November 5, 2014 }}. ''theiowarepublican.com''.</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nAfter winning the Republican primary in June 2014, Blum defeated Democrat [[Pat Murphy (Iowa politician)|Pat Murphy]] with 51% of the vote in the November 4, 2014, general election. This was considered a surprise Republican victory, as the seat had a D+5 Cook [[PVI Score]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cookpolitical.com/application/writable/uploads/2012_PVI_by_District.pdf|title=Cook PVI website|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Blum succeeded Democrat [[Bruce Braley]], who vacated his U.S. House seat to run unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rod Blum wins 1st Congressional District race|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/2014/11/05/iowa-first-congressional-district-rod-blum-pat-murphy-election/18433935/|accessdate=February 23, 2016|work=Des Moines Register|date=November 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Iowa's1stcongressionaldistrict2016electionresultsbycounty.png|thumb|Map showing the results of the 2016 election in Iowa's First congressional district by county]]\nBlum ran for reelection in 2016.<ref name=cahn>{{cite news|last1=Cahn|first1=Emily|title=Blum Says Others Will Support Him If Republicans Don't|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/blum-running-re-election-without-party-behind/|accessdate=February 23, 2016|publisher=Roll Call|date=June 12, 2015}}</ref> He was unopposed in the Republican primary. He faced Democrat [[Monica Vernon]] in the general election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barton|first1=Thomas|title=After conceding, Murphy endorses Vernon in effort to unseat Blum|url=http://www.thonline.com/news/breaking/article_28c8a43e-6929-507f-88e2-ba374b11ff68.html|accessdate=June 8, 2016|publisher=Telegraph Herald|date=June 8, 2016}}</ref> Blum defeated Vernon with 54% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iowa U.S. House 1st District Results: Rod Blum Wins|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/iowa-house-district-1-blum-vernon|accessdate=November 16, 2016|publisher=The New York Times|date=November 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Electoral history===\n{{Election box begin no change| title= Iowa's 1st congressional district election (2016)}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Rod Blum (incumbent)\n  |votes      = 206,903\n  |percentage = 54%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Monica Vernon \n  |votes      = 177,403\n  |percentage = 46%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change|\n  |party      = ([[Write-in candidate|Write-ins]])\n  |candidate  = Others\n  |votes      = 671\n  |percentage = 0.2%\n}}\n{{Election box total no change|\n  |votes      = 384,977\n  |percentage = 100.00%\n}}\n\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change| title=Iowa's 1st congressional district election (2014)}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Rod Blum\n  |votes      = 145,383\n  |percentage = 51%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = [[Pat Murphy (Iowa politician)|Pat Murphy]]\n  |votes      = 138,335\n  |percentage = 49%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change|\n  |party      = ([[Write-in candidate|Write-ins]])\n  |candidate  = Others\n  |votes      = 348\n  |percentage = 0.12%\n}}\n{{Election box total no change|\n  |votes      = 284,066\n  |percentage = 100.00%\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link without swing|\n  |winner     = Republican Party (United States)\n  |loser      = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade|Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade]] (chair)\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n**[[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Information Technology|Subcommittee on Information Technology]]\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=|date=|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*Congressional Slovak Caucus<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lynch|first1=James|title=Blum joins Congressional Slovak Caucus|url=http://www.thegazette.com/subject/news/government/blum-joins-congressional-slovak-caucus-20150601|accessdate=February 23, 2016|publisher=The Gazette|date=June 1, 2015}}</ref>\n*Congressional Term Limits Caucus<ref>{{cite news|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|title=Lawmakers form Term Limits Caucus|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/237738-lawmakers-form-term-limits-caucus|accessdate=February 23, 2016|publisher=The Hill|date=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Freedom Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/the-hard-line-republicans-who-pushed-john-boehner-out|first1=Carl|last1=Bialik|first2=Aaron|last2= Bycoffe|title=The Hard-Line Republicans Who Pushed John Boehner Out|date=September 25, 2015|work=[[FiveThirtyEight]]|accessdate=September 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nBlum describes himself as a \"Tea Party Republican,\" and has said that \"the Tea Party is what the Republican Party should have always been.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wcfcourier.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/rod-blum-thinks-economy-is-key/article_5fc849a0-a067-5427-9071-6d5c7acbbf23.html|title=Rod Blum thinks economy is key|last=Ericson|first=Jon|work=Waterloo Cedar Falls Courier|accessdate=February 26, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraphherald.com/news/tri-state/article_80157eb9-ed33-5e4f-b419-c72fba61ca01.html|title=Blum, Lange expound on telling topics|work=telegraphherald.com|accessdate=February 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of October 2017, Blum had voted with the Republican Party in 90% of votes in the [[115th United States Congress]] and voted in line with President Trump's position in 94% of the votes.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/rod-blum/|title=Tracking Rod Blum In The Age Of Trump|last=Bycoffe|first=Aaron|date=January 30, 2017|work=FiveThirtyEight|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://projects.propublica.org/represent/members/B001294-rod-blum|title=Represent|last=Willis|first=Derek|work=ProPublica|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Environment===\n[[File:Rod Blum official congressional photo.jpg|thumb|Congressman Rod Blum]]\nBlum has described himself as \"skeptical\" of the [[scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus]] that human activities are a primary contributor to [[climate change]].<ref name=\":4\" /> He said that the scientific community used to support the conjecture of [[global cooling]] and that \"most scientists' paychecks come from the federal government, and so right away that makes me a bit skeptical.\"<ref name=\":4\"/> Blum opposes federal regulation of greenhouse gas emissions.<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\nAs of February 2017, he had a 3% score with the [[League of Conservation Voters]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scorecard.lcv.org/moc/rod-blum|title=Check out Representative Rod Blum's Environmental Voting Record|work=League of Conservation Voters Scorecard|accessdate=February 26, 2017}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=January 2018}}\n\n===Health care===\nBlum favors \"fully repealing\" the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare).<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":4\"/> In 2017, Blum did not support the initial version of the  [[American Health Care Act of 2017]], the Republican Party's bill to repeal and replace Obamacare, saying that it \"doesn't do enough to lower premiums for hardworking Americans\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Noble|first1=Jason|title=King lone 'yes' vote on health care bill among Iowa's House members|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/politics/2017/03/22/heres-how-iowas-congressional-delegation-vote-health-care-bill/99501176|website=Des Moines Register|accessdate=April 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2017, Blum voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] and pass the revised version of the American Health Care Act.<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/|title=How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill|website=Washington Post|accessdate=May 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/04/politics/house-health-care-vote/index.html|title=How every member voted on health care bill|last=Staff|first=C.N.N.|website=CNN|access-date=May 4, 2017}}</ref> Blum said that the bill had been improved to his liking.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/05/08/iowa-congressman-walks-out-of-a-tv-interview-and-into-an-angry-town-hall-meeting|title=Iowa congressman walks out of a TV interview and into an angry town hall meeting|website=Washington Post|accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref> He described the bill as \"Trumpcare\" but also as \"Obamacare 2.0\" because \"We've probably changed 10, 20 percent of the bill is all.\"<ref name=\":6\"/> Blum said that \"AHCA will stabilize the market, lower premiums for Iowans, increase choices, reduce taxes, and protect people who have pre-existing conditions.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/2017/05/04/iowa-reps-young-blum-and-king-vote-yes-obamacare-replacement/310955001/|title=Iowa Reps. Young, Blum and King vote 'yes' on Obamacare replacement|work=Des Moines Register|accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAsked why he voted for the legislation before the impact of the bill had been assessed by the nonpartisan [[Congressional Budget Office]], Blum stated that there was an urgent need for a fix to Obamacare.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraphherald.com/news/politics/article_ab142b97-10a7-55c8-b3a4-466be71e91c2.html|title=Blum faces hostile crowd during town hall in hometown|last=Barton|first=Thomas|work=Telegraph Herald|access-date=May 9, 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/rob-blum-health-care-town-hall_us_5911190ae4b0d5d9049f60e7|title=Iowa Republican Congressman Feels Heat Over Health Care Vote|last=Bobic|first=Igor|date=May 9, 2017|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring his town halls in May 2017, Blum falsely claimed that if the current version of AHCA became law that coverage would not change for those on [[Medicaid]]. He also told his constituents, \"If you're getting your insurance through the group health care marketplace \u2014 your employer \u2014 nothing changes.\" This was found to be partly false when fact checked by [[National Public Radio]], as whether someone's insurance would change under the GOP bill depends on whether an employer is based in and purchases its insurance in a state that gets a waiver.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kodjak|first1=Alison|title=Fact-Checking Republicans' Defense of The GOP Health Bill|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2017/05/09/527627331/fact-checking-republicans-defense-of-the-gop-health-bill|website=NPR|accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref> Blum also said that AHCA would take care of the same people as the ACA; the ''Telegraph Herald'' wrote that under the AHCA, \"Insurers still would be prohibited from setting premiums based on health status and denying coverage to someone with a pre-existing condition. However, those who do not maintain continuous coverage could be charged higher premiums for a pre-existing condition\" and that states that seek waivers from the federal government would be allowed to charge older individuals up to five times as much as young people and to exempt insurers from a list of essential health benefits mandated by the ACA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraphherald.com/news/politics/article_ab142b97-10a7-55c8-b3a4-466be71e91c2.html|title=Blum faces hostile crowd during town hall in hometown|last=thomas.barton@thmedia.com|first=THOMAS J. BARTON|work=TelegraphHerald.com|access-date=May 3, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Blum walked out of a local television interview after being asked why his staff was pre-screening constituents who planned to attend his town hall meetings.<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Keefe |first=Ed |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/05/08/iowa-congressman-walks-out-of-a-tv-interview-and-into-an-angry-town-hall-meeting/ |title=Iowa congressman walks out of a TV interview and into an angry town hall meeting |publisher=The Washington Post |date=May 8, 2017 |accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HLHrPik1Aog |title=Rep. Rod Blum quickly ends interview with reporter Josh Scheinblum |publisher=YouTube |date=May 8, 2017 |accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Economic issues and tax reform===\nBlum favors \"a constitutional amendment to balance the budget and limit spending.\"<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://iowapublicradio.org/post/candidate-profile-rod-blum#stream/0|title=Candidate Profile:  Rod Blum|last=Perkins|first=Lindsey Moon, Katherine|access-date=February 26, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Blum voted against legislation that would have averted a government shutdown.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wcfcourier.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/blum-king-vote-against-resolution-to-keep-open-government/article_f5abd901-43da-5827-8bac-34140beb59b4.html|title=Blum, King vote against resolution to keep open government|last=Crippes|first=Christinia|work=Waterloo Cedar Falls Courier|accessdate=February 26, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Discussing the government shutdown, Blum said, \"I think the Founding Fathers are smiling right now for the first time in a long time\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://globegazette.com/news/local/rod-blum-discusses-house-freedom-caucus/article_2b399fa3-be3d-5452-88c4-614b981a2776.html|title=Rod Blum discusses House Freedom Caucus|last=Courier|first=CHRISTINIA CRIPPES Waterloo|work=Mason City Globe Gazette|access-date=February 26, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, in light of a $2 billion redevelopment of D.C.'s Southwest waterfront, Blum said that Washington D.C. \"needs a recession.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2016/03/23/iowa-congressman-says-d-c-needs-a-recession-because-it-has-cranes-everywhere/|title=Iowa congressman says D.C. needs a recession because it has 'cranes everywhere'|date=March 23, 2016|publisher=Washington Post|last1=Stein|first1=Perry|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonian.com/2016/03/23/iowa-congressman-rod-blum-wants-dc-recession-the-wharf|title=This Iowa Congressman Really Hates the Wharf in Southwest DC'|date=March 23, 2016|publisher=Washingtonian|last1=Freed|first1=Benjamin|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBlum opposes a mandatory increase in the federal minimum wage.<ref name=\":4\"/>\n\nBlum supports [[tax reform]] and voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=December 26, 2017|date=December 19, 2017}}</ref> After the vote passed, Blum tweeted that \"families...will see their tax home pay increase.\"<ref name=\"V122117\">{{cite web|last1=V|first1=Scott|title=Northwest Iowa Congressional Delegation Supportive Of Tax Plan|url=http://kiwaradio.com/local-news/northwest-iowa-congressional-delegation-supportive-of-tax-plan/|website=KIWA|accessdate=December 26, 2017|date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Government structure===\n\nBlum cast his first vote in Congress against [[John Boehner]]'s speakership,<ref name=\"cahn\"/> saying, \"I was elected by Iowans to stand up to the status quo in Washington, D.C., and I refuse to turn my back on them with my first vote... With congressional approval ratings at historic lows, it's time for our elected officials to listen to the people and rethink business as usual so we can move our country forward together.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/politics/2015/01/06/iowans-rod-blum-david-young-sworn-congressmen/21340979|title=In first vote, Blum rejects Boehner as speaker|work=Des Moines Register|accessdate=February 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[USA Today]]'', Blum has \"made it his central focus to change the way Congress treats itself by supporting efforts to strip away the trappings of elective office.\" Blum and Democrat [[Beto O'Rourke]] started the Congressional Term Limits Caucus. He co-sponsored legislation to end lawmakers' access to first class travel and luxury car leases, he supports ending the congressional pension system, and he has introduced a bill to institute a lifetime ban on lawmakers ever becoming lobbyists.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2015/05/07/rod-blum-iowa-congress/70942542/|title=Freshman Rod Blum flies solo on his mission to change Congress|date=May 7, 2015|publisher=USA Today|last1=Davis|first1=Susan|accessdate=February 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Blum returned $102,000 of his unspent 2015 office budget to the [[United States Treasury]] to help pay down the national debt. He did not confirm whether he planned to donate half of his congressional salary to charity, which he had pledged to do on his campaign website. Blum said: \"I'm not saying I didn't. I very well may have. But it's not something I'm going to comment on.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraphherald.com/news/article_0312729b-0d67-5b3b-baad-8d12a9bf3b02.html|title=Blum returns office money, mum on salary promises|last=Garbe|first=William|work=THonline.com|access-date=February 26, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBlum supports a constitutional amendment to enforce term limits for congressmen. When asked how many terms he was going to seek in an April 2015 interview, Blum responded, \"I'm not going to term limit myself. I definitely believe in term limits, but I don't believe in unilaterally disarming...Do I see myself being in the House of Representatives 10 years from now? No, I don't.\" <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraphherald.com/news/tri-state/article_276271f0-4e3e-586f-8b1d-62fd49e6bfbd.html|title=Rod Blum still above water with Republican Party, despite votes|last=Garbe|first=WilliamG|work=THonline.com|access-date=February 26, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration===\nBlum supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s first 2017 [[Executive Order 13769|executive order]], which was struck down by the courts. The order temporarily curtailed immigration from Iraq, Syria, Iran, Libya, Somalia, Sudan, and Yemen until better screening methods are devised. Blum stated that \"...The bottom line is they can't properly vet people coming from war-torn areas like Syria and Iraq. If we can't vet people properly, then we shouldn't be allowing them into our country. I'm supportive of that.\"<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump's travel ban; here's where the rest stand|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban|website=Denver Post|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Abortion===\nBlum opposes abortion.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/135714/rod-blum/#.WLNHuBKLSfQ|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Project Vote Smart|language=en-US|access-date=February 26, 2017}}</ref> He has voted to defund [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://wcfcourier.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/blum-supports-defunding-planned-parenthood/article_f985bbb5-3450-5ba6-afc5-81bec0da44ff.html|title=Blum supports defunding Planned Parenthood|last=Crippes|first=Christinia|work=Waterloo Cedar Falls Courier|access-date=February 26, 2017|language=en}}</ref> He supported creating a select committee to investigate [[Planned Parenthood 2015 undercover videos controversy|Planned Parenthood for allegedly selling fetal tissue]].<ref name=\":3\"/>\n\n===Drug policy===\n\nBlum has a \"B\" rating from [[NORML]] for his voting history regarding [[cannabis]]-related causes. Blum supports veterans having access to medical marijuana if recommended by their [[Veterans Health Administration]] doctor and if it is legal for medicinal purposes in their state of residence. He has voted in favor of federally funded programs regarding medical marijuana research.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=Iowa Scorecard|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/iowa|website=norml.org|accessdate=December 26, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT issues===\nBlum believes that same-sex marriage should be determined by states.<ref>{{Citation|last=Caffeinated Thoughts|title=Rod Blum Interview|date=October 10, 2013|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IyySBKPq9EM#t=783|accessdate=February 26, 2017}}</ref> In 2016, he voted against an amendment aimed at upholding an executive order barring discrimination against LGBT employees by federal contractors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/politics/2016/05/19/david-young-among-those-who-switched-vote-lgbt-measure/84606832|title=David Young among those who switched vote on LGBT measure|work=Des Moines Register|accessdate=February 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Donald Trump===\nIn February 2017, he voted against a resolution that would have directed the U.S. House to request ten years of Trump's tax returns, which would then have been reviewed by the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means Committee]] in a closed session.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indy100.com/article/republican-vote-donald-trump-tax-president-united-states-229-185-congress-7603851|title=These are all the Republicans who don't want you to see Donald Trump's tax returns|date=February 28, 2017|work=indy100|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBlum supported Trump's May 10, 2017, firing of FBI Director [[James Comey]], saying \"it's probably time for Comey to go.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/10/politics/rod-blum-town-hall/index.html|title=Father of child with disabilities confronts Blum at town hall|last=CNN|first=Eugene Scott|website=CNN|access-date=May 10, 2017}}</ref> The FBI was at the time conducting a criminal probe into possible ties between Trump associates and Russia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/10/us/politics/congress-statements-comey.html|title=How Every Lawmaker Has Reacted to Comey's Firing So Far|last=Fessenden|first=Audrey Carlsen, Kenan Davis, Jasmine C. Lee, K. k Rebecca Lai, Ford|date=May 10, 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=May 10, 2017|last2=Pearce|first2=Adam|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Trade ===\nIn June 2018, amid a brewing trade war between the United States and China, Blum urged the Trump administration \"to avoid a trade war\".<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/17/business/economy/iowa-trade-midterms.html|title=Trade War Worries Iowa Republicans in a Close House Race|access-date=2018-09-01|language=en}}</ref> In July 2018, Blum thanked Trump for \"having political courage to renegotiate these trade deals.\"<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n==Ethics inquiry==\nIn February 2018, the [[Associated Press]] reported that Blum had \"violated House ethics rules by failing to disclose his role in a company that he formed.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/politics/2018/02/21/rod-blum-didnt-disclose-he-director-internet-company-which-posted-testimonial-his-current-chief-staf/359391002/|title=Rod Blum didn't disclose that he was a director for an internet company \u2014 which posted a testimonial from his current chief of staff|last1=Foley|first1=Ryan|date=February 21, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018|publisher=Des Moines Register|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Blum was listed as a director of internet marketing company Tin Moon Corp. when it was incorporated in May 2016. Tin Moon's address is listed in the same Dubuque office as a construction software company Blum owns, Digital Canal, and Blum's chief of staff was featured in online testimonials for Tin Moon. Blum said he made an oversight in failing to disclose his ties to the company on his personal financial disclosure, and that the company was \"basically worth less than $1,000 and not doing business in 2016.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/politics/2018/02/22/rod-blum-says-undisclosed-firm-wasnt-doing-business/365162002/|title=Rod Blum says undisclosed firm wasn't 'doing business'|last1=Foley|first1=Ryan|date=February 22, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018|publisher=Des Moines Register|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In March 2018, Tin Moon removed Blum from its website.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kcrg.com/content/news/Company-linked-to-Iowa-congressman-scrubs-any-mention-of-him-476965193.html|title=Company linked to Iowa congressman scrubs any mention of him|date=March 15, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018|publisher=ABC 9|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, the Office of Congressional Ethics referred an ethics investigation case into Blum to the House Ethics Committee. The House Ethics Committee announced that it would release its findings prior to December 17, 2018.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/vulnerable-rod-blum-house-ethics-inquiry|title=Vulnerable Rod Blum Under House Ethics Inquiry|last=Tully-McManus|first=Katherine|date=2018-09-04|work=Roll Call|access-date=2018-09-06|last2=Tully-McManus|first2=Katherine|language=en|last3=Tully-McManus|first3=Katherine|last4=Tully-McManus|first4=Katherine}}</ref> Blum described the inquiry into him as a \"crusade of personal destruction\" waged by the \"radical left\".<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nBlum was born and raised in Dubuque, the son of Celeste M. (Van Der Meulen) and Wallace Lee Blum, a [[World War II]] veteran.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphherald.com/obituaries/article_29521a57-69d7-5ba5-83ff-3250372d6f29.html|title=Celeste M. Blum|first=TELEGRAPH|last=HERALD|publisher=}}</ref> He resides in Dubuque with his wife, Karen, and their five children.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/135714 \"Project Vote Smart \u2013 The Voter's Self Defense System\"]. ''Project Vote Smart''; accessed May 11, 2017.</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://blum.house.gov/ U.S. Congressman Rod Blum] official U.S. House site\n*[http://rodblum.com/ Campaign website]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Iowa/Government/Federal/US_H